3. User Setup: User Account Properties Window

Use the User Setup: User Account Properties window to display the
current properties for the icon selected in the User Setup window. You
can change the following properties (if you have appropriate
permission):

   o The Login ID is what the user enters at the login ID prompt. All
     the files and folders that the user owns are identified with this
     ID.

   o The Comment is usually the full name of the user, but can contain
     any text you choose.

   o Type refers to whether or not a Desktop environment is created
     for a user. If a user is a Nondesktop user, they can only
     execute programs from the character based UNIX System prompt.

   o GUI specifies whether the Desktop is presented with an OPEN LOOK
     or a Motif graphical user interface (GUI).

If you click on the Extra Options box, a window with the following
properties appears.

   o The Home Folder is the folder where the user stores their files
     and folders. For example, for a user called zorb, the Home Folder
     might be /home/zorb.

   o X-terminal Name is the name of the system where the Desktop is
     displayed when you don't log in from the console. For example,
     if you use an X-terminal for logging in, enter the system name of
     the X-terminal. You can also include the display number, such as
     :0 or :1. If you don't include the display number, :0 is
     assumed.

   o The Shell is the UNIX System shell that is used when the Desktop
     is not used. Two shells are /usr/bin/sh and /usr/bin/ksh.

   o User ID: User ID is a unique number assigned to each account. It
     is used internally by UNIX SVR4.2 to manage files, processes, and
     so on, that are used by users.

   o The Select Group From box lists available groups. Each user must
     belong to a group. Select a group from the list. Use the
     scrollbar, if present, to view additional groups.

The buttons available from the User Setup: User Account Properties
window are:

